==================================================
6. SCREEN REQUIREMENTS
==================================================

----------------------------------------
A. VARIATION LAB
----------------------------------------

Purpose:
This is the command center of the project.

Requirements:
- header with story title, branch context, and status badge
- left panel with branch tree / lineage map
- main panel with selected variation preview
- actions:
  - Create New Variation
  - Browse Ranked Variations
  - Continue Draft
- selected node card should show:
  - variation title
  - source version
  - changed variable
  - short summary
  - score snapshot
  - number of reviews
  - fork count
  - status

Behavior:
- clicking a node updates the main preview
- clicking actions routes correctly
- use mock branch data with at least one original story and several child variations

----------------------------------------
B. CREATE VARIATION
----------------------------------------

Purpose:
Force the creator to define the change precisely.

Must include the following steps in one guided flow or stepper:

Step 1: Select Source
- options:
  - Original Version
  - Ranked Variation
  - My Previous Draft
- if Ranked Variation is selected:
  - show searchable or scrollable variation cards
  - each card includes score and fork count

Step 2: Define Variable Change
Fields:
- What variable are you changing?
- Type of change
- Describe the change clearly
- Why does this change matter?
- Expected narrative effect
- Confidence level

Type of change options:
- character trait
- decision
- social rule
- environmental condition
- time condition
- moral constraint
- other

Expected narrative effect options:
- stronger conflict
- system instability
- emotional shift
- moral inversion
- alternate ending
- new character arc

Right-side reference panel:
- source summary
- changed variable summary
- expected downstream effects

Step 3: Draft the Variation
Two-column layout:
- left = source reference
- right = editable draft area

Required sections:
- Variation Summary
- What changed from source
- Immediate consequences
- Long-term consequences
- Why this version deserves evaluation

Actions:
- Save Draft
- Preview Structured Diff
- Submit for Review

Validation Gate:
Before submission, show a completeness checklist.
Block submission if required sections are incomplete.

----------------------------------------
C. REVIEW VARIATION
----------------------------------------

Purpose:
Reviewers evaluate through structured lenses, not vague opinion.

Layout:
- top summary header
- three-column layout:
  - source
  - candidate variation
  - review form

Review form requirements:

Quick scores from 1 to 10:
- Narrative coherence
- Internal logic
- Emotional power
- Originality
- Long-term sustainability
- Adaptation potential

Reviewer lens selector:
- Skeptic
- Defender
- Systems Thinker
- Audience Proxy
- Character Analyst
- Adaptation Judge

Structured critique prompts:
- strongest element
- weakest element
- where the variation becomes unstable
- what should not be changed
- whether this version improves on the source

Evidence tags:
- contradiction
- shallow motivation
- weak payoff
- strong escalation
- better thematic clarity
- more cinematic
- emotionally weaker
- stronger structure

Recommendation:
- advance to ranking
- revise before ranking
- reject for now

Also include creator response cards below or in a separate section:
For each review item, creator can choose:
- Accept
- Reject
- Partially Accept
with a short required justification field

----------------------------------------
D. RANKED VARIATIONS BOARD
----------------------------------------

Purpose:
Show reviewed variations as a competitive and interpretable system.

Must support:
- table view
- card view toggle
- filters
- sort controls

Columns or card fields:
- Rank
- Variation title
- Source branch
- Overall score
- Coherence
- Originality
- Stability
- Emotional impact
- Review count
- Fork count
- Status

Filters:
- by story
- by branch
- by score range
- by reviewer consensus
- by most forked
- by newest
- by cinematic potential

Sort options:
- highest overall
- most original
- most stable
- most debated
- best adaptation potential

When clicking a ranking entry:
Open a detail drawer or side panel with:
- score radar or score summary blocks
- consensus summary
- strongest comments
- biggest disagreements
- creator defense summary
- source lineage

Actions in drawer:
- Open Full Comparison
- Fork This Variation
- View Branch Tree

----------------------------------------
E. FORK RANKED VARIATION
----------------------------------------

Purpose:
Allow branching from a strong ranked version while preserving lineage.

Requirements:
Top parent card shows:
- title
- rank badge
- score snapshot
- creator
- reason it ranked high

Fork form fields:
- New branch title
- What new variable will you change now?
- What are you preserving from the parent variation?
- What are you intentionally disrupting?

Show lineage preview:
Original → Ranked Variation → New Fork

Action:
- Create Fork

Behavior after create:
- route user into create/draft state for the new fork
- inherited parent context must remain visible in a reference panel

----------------------------------------
F. COMPARISON VIEW
----------------------------------------

Purpose:
This is the proof screen of the platform.
It must make narrative difference legible.

Layout:
- side-by-side comparison
- left = parent/source variation
- right = selected variation/fork
- center or inline diff blocks showing key change

Must show:
- changed variable
- narrative consequences
- emotional shift
- structural gain/loss
- stability gain/loss

Tabs:
- Summary
- Character impact
- World/system impact
- Ending divergence
- Reviewer verdicts

Bottom section:
A synthesized “Which version is stronger, and why?” area based on mock structured review data.

Actions:
- Vote
- Review
- Fork right version
- Return to rankings

